      {
        "id": 2337147,
        "name": "Gerhard P.  (P r @ \u20ac s e n t)",
        "username": "Gerhard_P",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/g/8baadc/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2018-01-16T09:41:37.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"c fu\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n c fu:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>It\u2019s what we now know as Coteaux Bourguignons. It\u2019s wines made from grapes outside of the traditional CDN/CDB that we know from burgundy. This one is 100% Pinot supposedly.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>This one is 100% Pinot supposedly.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</blockquote>\n<p>No, I doubt that - most probably incl. Gamay - otherwise it would be called \u201cBourgogne Pinot noir\u201d \u2026</p>\n<blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>It\u2019s wines made from grapes outside of the traditional CDN/CDB that we know from burgundy \u2026</p>\n</blockquote>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Not necessarily, it\u00b4s outside \u201cbetter\u201d Appellations like Volnay, Pommard, Monthelie, Auxey-Duresses etc. \u2026 or partially from \u201cwithin\u201d, but planted with Gamay \u2026 (so not entitled to the \u201cbetter\u201d AOC).</p>\n<p>Sure it can also be from farther South like Macon or even Beaujolais \u2026 we\u00b4ll never know exactly \u2026</p>",
        "post_number": 7,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 9,
        "updated_at": "2022-06-03T02:37:32.145Z",
        "reply_count": 0,
